---
const doctrine = [
  ['Warm, not nostalgic', 'Human and held, not retro for its own sake.'],
  ['Serif for thought', 'Mono keeps structure visible while prose carries the argument.'],
  ['Blue is a signal', 'Accent where attention matters, not as a wash.'],
  ['Whitespace is operational', 'Breathing room creates pacing and room for judgment.'],
  ['Reveal, do not barrage', 'Information should unfold in layers.'],
  ['Composition over templating', 'Each page should look arranged for its subject.'],
];
---

<div class="essay-page design-page">
  <section class="page-hero-simple">
    <p class="eyebrow">Principles</p>
    <h1 class="page-display-title">Design should feel authored.</h1>
    <p class="page-lede">
      GalexC should not feel like an AI dashboard that borrowed nicer type. It should
      feel composed, editorial, and quietly deliberate - more like a publication,
      notebook, or field manual than a SaaS shell. That choice is not cosmetic. It
      signals how the product thinks.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="page-grid-two design-compare-grid">
    <article class="page-module page-module-panel compare-panel compare-panel-dense">
      <p class="eyebrow">Dashboard instinct</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Dense panes</li>
        <li>Constant controls</li>
        <li>Urgent prompts</li>
        <li>Interface churn</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    <article class="page-module page-module-panel compare-panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Editorial instinct</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Quiet hierarchy</li>
        <li>Readable measures</li>
        <li>Room for notes</li>
        <li>Emphasis only where it matters</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="page-module design-anatomy">
    <div class="module-heading-row">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Surface as posture</p>
        <h2 class="page-section-title">Visual decisions map to operator posture</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="page-grid-two design-specimen-grid">
      <article class="page-module page-module-panel design-specimen">
        <p class="eyebrow">Specimen spread</p>
        <h3>A page should feel composed enough to think inside.</h3>
        <div class="design-specimen__rule"></div>
        <p>
          Big serif hierarchy for thought. A measured reading column for the actual
          argument. Small mono notes for structure. Blue only where emphasis is earned.
        </p>
      </article>
      <aside class="page-module page-module-panel anatomy-notes">
        <p class="eyebrow">Anatomy</p>
        <div class="anatomy-notes__item">
          <strong>Breathing room</strong>
          <p>Whitespace suggests confidence and pacing, not emptiness.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="anatomy-notes__item">
          <strong>Quiet rule</strong>
          <p>Thin dividers keep rhythm visible without turning the page into chrome.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="anatomy-notes__item">
          <strong>Marginal note</strong>
          <p>Micro-labels let the system explain itself without shouting.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="anatomy-notes__item">
          <strong>Accent discipline</strong>
          <p>The blue only appears where attention or interaction truly matters.</p>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-grid-two page-grid-two-wide-right">
    <article class="page-module">
      <p class="eyebrow">Why this matters</p>
      <p>
        An authored, editorial, calm, durable surface communicates the same values as
        the system beneath it: bounded work over chaos, legibility over novelty,
        memory over ephemera, and confidence without noise. The interface should feel
        kept, not consumed.
      </p>
    </article>
    <aside class="page-module page-module-panel doctrine-grid">
      <p class="eyebrow">Visual doctrine</p>
      {
        doctrine.map(([title, body]) => (
          <div class="doctrine-grid__item">
            <p class="doctrine-grid__title">{title}</p>
            <p>{body}</p>
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </aside>
  </section>
</div>
